nding scientists can receive single digit equity percentages, </span><stron=
g>if they even receive any equity at all</strong><span>. In a world where t=
heir work can create billions of dollars of value, many biotechnologists ar=
e capturing miniscule fractions of these returns.</span></p><p style=3D"col=
or: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>=
The problem here isn&#8217;t just financial. </span><strong>Ownership has a=
n important consequence: control over the direction of a company.</strong><=
span> A central component of venture creation is the process of building ou=
t a management team of executives who have experience bringing drugs to mar=
ket. This means that scientists and engineers often don&#8217;t steer the t=
rajectory of new companies. Leave it to the professionals! While this can b=
e effective for executing within an existing paradigm, it doesn&#8217;t for=
ge new ones. Google and Facebook weren&#8217;t built by former IBM executiv=
es, they were built by young programmers exploring totally different approa=
ches to technology development and company culture. </span><strong>In the a=
ftermath, we now have an existence proof for the fact that young engineers =
can build and lead massive generational companies.</strong></p><p style=3D"=
color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><sp=
an>Things are starting to change. While biotech has traditionally been the =
realm of only specialist investors, tech VCs have made a serious entry. The=
se investors have brought some of the dynamics of tech entrepreneurship wit=
h them. Since making their first biotech investment in Ginkgo Bioworks (rea=
d more about that story </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/5fb=
